Borders most common cancers by sex…

borders_common_cancers_1996_sex <- incidence_by_hb_name_join %>% 
  select(cancer_site, year, sex, hb_name, incidences_all_ages) %>% 
  filter(cancer_site != "All cancer types" 
         & hb_name == "NHS Borders" 
         & sex != "All") %>% 
  group_by(cancer_site, sex) %>% 
  summarise(total_cases_of_cancer = sum(incidences_all_ages)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(total_cases_of_cancer))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'cancer_site'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
borders_common_cancers_1996_sex %>% 
  filter(total_cases_of_cancer > 500) %>% 
  ggplot()+
  aes(x = reorder(cancer_site, total_cases_of_cancer), 
      y = total_cases_of_cancer,

  coord_flip()+

       y = "Type of Cancer",

       fill = "Sex") +
  geom_text(aes(label = total_cases_of_cancer), 
            size = 3, vjust = -0.25, position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+
  theme_bw()

Looked up crude rate but I’m not 100% sure how I would use it: A crude rate is defined as the total number of events, or count, divided by the mid-year total population of the selected geography and multiplied by a constant, which is a multiple of 10. Typical constants used for public health rates include 100, 1,000, 10,000, or 100,000.

BUT considering the standardised incidence ratio: an SIR is the ratio of the observed number of cancer cases to the expected number of cases multiplied by 100. An SIR of 100 indicates that the number of cancer cases observed in the population evaluated is equal to the number of cancer cases expected in the comparison or “normal” population. This is why in “incidence_at_scotland_level” all the SIR are 100.

borders_incidences_sex %>% 
    ggplot()+

      y = standardised_incidence_ratio,

       subtitle = "January 1996 to December 2020")+
